{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/thinking-in-coordinate-transforms-6c9f0cb7cf07", "time": 1683017129.356161, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/thinking-in-coordinate-transforms-6c9f0cb7cf07/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Thinking in coordinate transforms | by Paul Hiemstra | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Thinking in coordinate transforms", "description": "Coordinate transforms are extremely useful mathematical operations that can reduce the dimensionality of your data (PCA), engineer a useful set of features (tsfresh) or project the Earth onto a 2D\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://github.com/PaulHiemstra/simple_eq_paper/blob/master/simple_eq_article.ipynb", "anchor_text": "the article on Github", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis", "anchor_text": "PCA", "paragraph_index": 1}, {"url": "https://tsfresh.readthedocs.io/en/latest/", "anchor_text": "tsfresh", "paragraph_index": 1}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_map_projections", "anchor_text": "map projections", "paragraph_index": 1}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform", "anchor_text": "Fast Fourier transform", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_signal_processing", "anchor_text": "DSP", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equalization_(audio)", "anchor_text": "equalizer", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "https://scipy-lectures.org/intro/scipy/auto_examples/plot_fftpack.html", "anchor_text": "this link", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/paul-hiemstra-77030b20/", "anchor_text": "on LinkedIn", "paragraph_index": 14}], "all_paragraphs": ["You can also read the article on Github including full reproducible code", "Coordinate transforms are extremely useful mathematical operations that can reduce the dimensionality of your data (PCA), engineer a useful set of features (tsfresh) or project the Earth onto a 2D map (map projections). Understanding what these transforms do takes quite a bit of abstract imagination. A key observation is that after the coordinate transform the data has not changed, just the way we describe the data.", "In this article we focus on a coordinate transformation called a Fast Fourier transform or FFT. An FFT decomposes a timeseries signal into a series of base frequency waves. FFT\u2019s are frequently used in digital signal processing (DSP), but can also be used to generate useful features from timeseries for machine learning algorithms. In this article we will use an FFT to build a very crude equalizer.", "But first we will start with a very simple example. We take the following two sine waves (example based on this link):", "where time is on the x-axis, and amplitude on the y-axis. The first sine wave has a frequency of 5 Hz, the second of 2 Hz. We combine these waves together with a small amount of random noise into one signal.", "Next we run the FFT to transform the combined signal:", "so instead of using time and amplitude as the coordinate axes to describe our data, the FFT uses the base frequencies and a coefficient that describes how strongly these base frequency are represented in the input signal. Note that time is no longer a factor, the FFT represents the entire input signal.", "To show how our FFT broke down our signal into base frequencies we calculate importance (or power) of each of these frequencies:", "which nicely shows the 2 and 5 Hz signals we used to construct the combined input signal to the FFT.", "Using the inverse FFT (iFFT) we can also reverse the coordinate transform, and get back our original signal. Here we first eliminate some of the higher base frequencies before reconstructing the signal:", "which nicely shows that the 5 Hz signal was filtered from the combined input signal. This essentially is how an equalizer can change the importance of certain base frequencies in the input sound signal. Note that a real equalizer does not outright eliminate base frequencies, but allows you to tweak their importance more subtely.", "We can use this same approach and apply it to a real audio sample:", "where the most power is concentrated in the lower bass and sub-bass frequencies, which lines up with the fact that the sample is of a bass drum. Next we use the same filtering technique we used for the sine waves on this audio signal. We eliminate any frequencies higher than 250 Hz:", "When zooming into the signal we can clearly see the small scale frequencies being eliminated, reducing the sound to just the bass frequencies.", "My name is Paul Hiemstra, and I work as a teacher and data scientist in the Netherlands. I am a mix between a scientist and a software engineer, and have a broad interest in everything related to data science. You can follow me here on medium, or on LinkedIn.", "If you enjoyed this article, you might also enjoy some of my other articles:", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Teacher and practitioner of data science."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F6c9f0cb7cf07&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fthinking-in-coordinate-transforms-6c9f0cb7cf07&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fthinking-in-coordinate-transforms-6c9f0cb7cf07&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text":